A base ten number system is one that is based on powers of ten (1, 
10, 100, 1000, and so on. For example, we write the number 123 the 
way we do because it contains 1 hundred, 2 tens, and 3 ones.

You can read about the concept of bases (with an emphasis on bases 
other than ten) here:

  Number bases
  http://mathforum.org/dr.math/faq/faq.bases.html

If you have any further questions, feel free to write back.


- Doctor Peterson, The Math Forum
